              <td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">Same formula for all adults</td>
              <td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">Separate formulas and ranges by sex</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="bg-gray-50 dark:bg-gray-800/50">
              <td class="px-4 py-3 font-medium text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">Best For</td>
              <td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">Quick population screening</td>
              <td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">Individual body composition assessment</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <h2>When to Use BMI</h2>
      <p>
        BMI is best suited for quick health screenings and population-level assessments. It requires only two measurements — weight and height — making it the simplest metric to track over time. Doctors use BMI as an initial screening tool during routine checkups because it correlates reasonably well with health outcomes across large populations. If you are looking for a simple, consistent way to monitor your weight trends and do not engage in intensive strength training, BMI provides a useful baseline. It is particularly effective for identifying individuals who may be at higher risk for conditions like type 2 diabetes, cardiovascular disease, and hypertension.
      </p>

      <div class="my-6"><%= render "shared/ad_slot", slot: "in_content" %></div>

      <h2>When to Use Body Fat Percentage</h2>
      <p>
        Body fat percentage is the superior metric when you need a more nuanced understanding of your body composition. It is essential for athletes, bodybuilders, and anyone who exercises regularly with weights, since BMI cannot distinguish between muscle mass and fat mass. A person who trains intensively may have a BMI classified as overweight while actually having a very lean, healthy physique. Body fat percentage also accounts for sex-specific differences, with separate healthy ranges for men and women. If you are tracking the effectiveness of a fitness program, body fat percentage tells you whether you are losing fat while preserving or building muscle — information that BMI simply cannot provide.
      </p>

      <h2>The Bottom Line</h2>
      <p>
        BMI and body fat percentage each have their place in health assessment. BMI excels as a fast, universal screening tool, while body fat percentage offers a deeper look at actual body composition. For most people, tracking both metrics provides the most complete picture. Use BMI for quick trend monitoring and body fat percentage for a more accurate assessment of your physical condition. Neither metric alone should be the sole basis for health decisions — consult a healthcare professional who can evaluate your full health profile, including blood work, fitness level, and medical history.
      </p>

      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <h3>Is body fat percentage more accurate than BMI?</h3>
      <p>
        Body fat percentage provides a more direct measure of body composition than BMI. While BMI only considers weight and height, body fat percentage estimates the actual proportion of fat tissue in your body. This makes body fat percentage more useful for athletes, muscular individuals, and anyone wanting to distinguish between fat mass and lean mass.
      </p>

      <h3>Why do doctors still use BMI if body fat percentage is better?</h3>
      <p>
        BMI remains widely used because it is quick, free, and requires no special equipment — just a scale and a tape measure for height. It is a reliable population-level screening tool that correlates well with health outcomes across large groups. Body fat measurement methods are more time-consuming and can require specialized equipment like calipers or DEXA scanners.
      </p>

      <h3>Can you have a normal BMI but high body fat?</h3>
      <p>
        Yes, this is sometimes called "skinny fat" or normal-weight obesity. A person can have a BMI in the normal range (18.5-24.9) while carrying a disproportionate amount of body fat and low muscle mass. This is common in sedentary individuals who do not engage in resistance training. Body fat percentage testing can reveal this hidden risk.
      </p>

      <h3>What is a healthy body fat percentage?</h3>
      <p>
        Healthy body fat ranges vary by sex. For men, 14-17% is considered fit, while 18-24% is average. For women, 21-24% is fit and 25-31% is average. Athletes typically fall in the 6-13% range for men and 14-20% for women. Essential fat levels — the minimum needed for basic health — are about 2-5% for men and 10-13% for women.
      </p>

      <h3>Which should I track for weight loss: BMI or body fat?</h3>
      <p>
        Ideally, track both. BMI gives you a simple baseline and is easy to measure consistently over time. Body fat percentage reveals whether you are losing fat versus muscle, which is critical for long-term health. If you can only track one, BMI is simpler for general weight management, but body fat percentage is more informative if you are also exercising regularly.
      </p>

